
1. What is a CSV file and why is it used?

CSV (Comma-Separated Values) is a row-based, delimiter-separated plain text format (RFC 4180) optimized for tabular data interchange. Each line represents a record; values separated by commas (,), quoted for embedding commas/quotes.

Engineering Characteristics:

• Schema-free (no type enforcement)
• Human-readable (UTF-8 text)
• Memory efficient (~30% smaller than Excel)
• Universal compatibility (pandas, R, SQL)
• Single-threaded parsing (fast for <10GB)

Production Use Cases:

✅ Data exchange (APIs → databases)
✅ Backup/export format
✅ ML training data ingestion
❌ Transactional writes (use SQL)



2. How do you display CSV data in a Streamlit app?

Static file loading → Interactive DataFrame rendering:

python
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd

# Local file
df = pd.read_csv('sales_data.csv')  # Auto-detects delimiter
st.dataframe(df, use_container_width=True)  # Interactive table

# URL-based
url_df = pd.read_csv('https://example.com/data.csv')
st.dataframe(url_df)

Memory Optimization: Pandas loads entire file → Use nrows=1000 for large files.



3. What is the difference between st.table() and st.dataframe()?

| Method         | Interactivity          | Performance    | Use Case               |
| -------------- | ---------------------- | -------------- | ---------------------- |
| st.table()     | Static (read-only)     | Fastest render | Reports, presentations |
| st.dataframe() | ✅ Sort, filter, search | 2-3x slower    | Data exploration       |


Implementation Decision Matrix:

python
# Static reporting (100K+ rows)
st.table(df)  # No JavaScript overhead

# Interactive analysis (<50K rows)
st.dataframe(df, height=400, hide_index=True)  # AgGrid integration

# Production: Pagination for large datasets
st.dataframe(df.head(1000), height=600)
if len(df) > 1000:
    st.caption(f"Showing first 1000 of {len(df):,} rows")



4. How can users upload their own CSV files in Streamlit?

Production-grade file upload with validation:

python
uploaded_file = st.file_uploader(
    "Upload CSV", 
    type=['csv', 'txt'],  # MIME type validation
    help="Max 50MB. CSV/TSV format only"
)

if uploaded_file:
    # Validate file size
    file_size = len(uploaded_file.getvalue())
    if file_size > 50 * 1024 * 1024:
        st.error("File too large (>50MB)")
    else:
        df = pd.read_csv(uploaded_file)
        
        # Data quality checks
        st.success(f"✅ Loaded {len(df):,} rows × {len(df.columns)} columns")
        st.info(f"Missing values: {df.isnull().sum().sum()}")
        
        col1, col2 = st.columns(2)
        with col1:
            st.dataframe(df.head(10))
        with col2:
            st.metric("Shape", f"{len(df):,} × {len(df.columns)}")


Edge Cases Handled:

• Delimiter detection (comma/semicolon/tab)
• Encoding issues (UTF-8 fallback)
• Header detection
• Large file warnings



5. How can you show charts using CSV data in Streamlit?

End-to-end visualization workflow:

python
# Auto-detect numeric columns for analysis
numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns
categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns

# Multi-chart layout
col1, col2, col3 = st.columns(3)

with col1:
    # Distribution analysis
    col = st.selectbox("Distribution", numeric_cols)
    st.altair_chart(
        alt.Chart(df).mark_bar().encode(
            x=alt.X(col, bin=True),
            y=alt.Y('count()')
        ).properties(width=200, height=200)
    )

with col2:
    # Correlation heatmap
    if len(numeric_cols) > 1:
        st.heatmap(df[numeric_cols].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')

with col3:
    # Categorical breakdown
    if len(categorical_cols) > 0:
        cat_col = st.selectbox("Category", categorical_cols)
        st.bar_chart(df[cat_col].value_counts())

# Advanced: Interactive scatter matrix
if st.checkbox("Show Scatter Matrix"):
    fig = px.scatter_matrix(df[numeric_cols], height=600)
    st.plotly_chart(fig, use_container_width=True)

Chart Selection Strategy:

1. Univariate: Histograms (distributions)
2. Bivariate: Scatter (correlations)  
3. Multivariate: Heatmaps (feature relationships)
4. Categorical: Bar charts (counts)

Production Deployment Considerations

📁 File Handling:
• Max upload: 200MB (configurable)
• Temporary storage: /tmp (auto-cleaned)
• Encoding: UTF-8 with BOM detection

⚡ Performance:
• Chunked reading: pd.read_csv(chunksize=10000)
• Column selection: usecols=['key1','key2']
• Lazy evaluation: dask for >1GB files

🔒 Security:
• Validate file extensions
• Virus scanning (ClamAV integration)
• Row/column limits

